==Old English==
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''faran'', from Indo-European ''*per-''.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian ''[[fara]]'', Old Saxon ''faran'' (Dutch ''[[varen]]''), Old High German ''faran'' (German ''[[fahren]]''), Old Norse ''[[fara]]'', Gothic [[𐍆𐌰𐍂𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πέραν]], Latin [[portare]], Slavic ''*pьratī'' (Old Church Slavonic {{RUchar|[[перѫ]]}}, Russian [[переть]]).

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈfaran/}}

===Verb===
(ġe)'''faran''' (class VI strong)
# to [[go]], to [[travel]]
#:''Nu wylle ic faran'': Now I will go.

===Related words===
*[[feran|fēran]]
*[[faru]]
*[[fyrd]]

